Project Specification
Minimal Tracker-Based DAW (JACK + FLTK)
1. Design Philosophy

This application is:

A lightweight tracker-style DAW

Focused on live-played music and clean structure

Deterministic and real-time safe

Minimal in effects and DSP

Not a plugin host platform

Not a Renoise clone

Not a “modern glossy DAW”

The system favors:

Stability over extensibility

Built-in DSP over plugin ecosystems

Clear module boundaries

Fixed-size structures in real-time paths

Simplicity over feature density

2. System Architecture Overview

The application is divided into strictly separated subsystems:

Core Engine

Audio Engine (JACK Backend)

Sequencer / Tracker Engine

Instrument Subsystem

Built-in DSP / Mixer Subsystem

Sample & Audio Editor

File Format & Import

GUI Subsystem (FLTK)

Infrastructure Utilities

Real-time and non-real-time code are strictly separated.

3. Core Engine
Responsibilities

Application startup/shutdown

Subsystem initialization

Thread creation

Transport control

Global configuration

Thread Model

JACK Audio Thread (real-time)

GUI Thread (FLTK main loop)

Worker Thread(s)

File loading/saving

Time stretch

Resampling

Sample processing

Real-Time Rules

Inside audio callback:

No memory allocation

No locks

No file I/O

No dynamic container resizing

No GUI interaction

Communication between threads via:

Lock-free queues

Double-buffered state blocks

4. Audio Engine (JACK)
Backend

JACK audio

JACK MIDI

Responsibilities

Audio buffer processing

MIDI input/output

Transport synchronization

Input capture for recording

External instrument audio capture

Ports

Stereo master output

Optional subgroup outputs

Optional track input ports

MIDI in/out ports

All routing inside engine is internal except explicit JACK connections.

5. Sequencer / Tracker Engine
Pattern Model

Maximum 512 rows per pattern

Fixed row resolution

Configurable lines per beat

Fixed-size memory layout (RT safe)

Track Model

Each track:

Exactly one instrument

Multiple subtracks (note columns)

Maximum 16 subtracks per track

Each subtrack:

One note per row

One effect command per row

Pattern List

Ordered sequence

Add/remove/duplicate pattern

Pattern reuse allowed

6. Minimal Tracker Effect Set

Only musically meaningful and manageable effects are supported.

Transport Effects (Global)

Set Tempo

Set Lines per Beat

Pattern Break

Pattern Jump

Pattern Delay

Amplitude Effects (Per Track)

Set Volume

Volume Slide Up

Volume Slide Down

Fade over rows

Pitch Effects

Portamento to Note

Arpeggio (simple)

Pitch Offset

Panning

Set Pan

Pan Slide

Timing

Retrigger

Note Delay

Instrument Macro

Macro Control (4–8 parameters per instrument)

Tracker only controls macros, not raw plugin parameters

No:

Multi-effect columns

Tick-level complexity (initially row-based timing)

Exotic IT/XM compatibility quirks

Effects are row-based for simplicity.

7. Instrument Subsystem

All instruments implement a unified interface:

note_on()

note_off()

process_audio()

set_macro()

reset()

serialize_state()

restore_state()

Supported Instrument Types
1. Sample Instrument

Stereo samples

RAM-based

Basic ADSR

Pitch control

Loop support (optional)

2. SF2 Instrument (Optional Later)

Embedded SF2 engine

3. Simple Internal Synth (Optional Future)

Basic subtractive synth

Very limited parameters

4. MIDI Output Instrument

Sends MIDI to JACK

Optional audio return via mixer input

No full plugin hosting in initial design.

8. Built-in DSP / Mixer Subsystem

Instead of relying on LV2/LADSPA, the system provides a minimal internal DSP set.

Channel Structure

Each track has:

Volume

Pan

Mute

Solo

Insert DSP chain (fixed small size)

Built-in DSP Modules

Minimal, stable, deterministic.

Core DSP List

Gain

Simple 3-Band EQ

Low-pass Filter

High-pass Filter

Simple Delay

Basic Reverb (Schroeder type)

Compressor (simple RMS)

Saturation (optional)

Each DSP module:

Fixed parameter set

No GUI windows

Controlled via mixer panel

RT safe

No dynamic memory

Insert Chain

Small fixed maximum (e.g. 4 effects per track)

Reorderable

Enable/disable

No dynamic plugin loading

Routing

Track → optional subgroup → master

External audio input per track optional

9. Sample & Audio Editor
Responsibilities

Record stereo input

Create sample instrument

Edit samples offline

Editing Operations

Cut

Copy

Paste

Crop

Normalize

Volume change

Time stretch (libsndtouch or equivalent)

Resample (libsamplerate)

All heavy processing in worker thread.

Samples loaded entirely into RAM (initial design).

10. File Format
Container

tar.gz archive

Structure:

song.json
samples/
patterns/
instruments/

song.json Contains

Global settings

Track definitions

Pattern data

Instrument assignments

Mixer settings

DSP parameters

Macro mappings

JSON chosen for:

Simplicity

Human readability

Debugging ease

11. GUI Subsystem (FLTK)
Layout

Main window tabs:

Tracker

Mixer

Audio Editor

Settings / File

Tracker, Mixer, and Editor detachable as independent windows.

Tracker UI

Custom FLTK widget:

Manual grid drawing

Monospace font

Row highlighting

Keyboard-focused editing

Pattern list view

Keybinding presets:

FastTracker 2

Impulse Tracker

Renoise

Fully customizable

Mixer UI

Channel strips

Insert DSP controls inline

Subgroup view

Level meters

Spectral analyzer (optional per channel or master)

No floating plugin windows.

12. Development Phases
Phase 1

JACK engine

Sample instrument

Tracker playback

Basic mixer (volume/pan)

Phase 2

Built-in DSP modules

Project save/load

Audio recording

Phase 3

Sample editor

Macro system

Transport effects

Phase 4

Optional SF2 or simple synth

Import XM / MIDI

13. Scope Discipline

The project intentionally excludes:

Large plugin ecosystems

Unlimited effect chains

Complex automation lanes

Per-tick legacy tracker quirks

GUI-heavy workflow

Massive feature accumulation

The system is meant to remain:

Focused

Predictable

Hackable

Stable

Musically useful

Final Character of the Application

This is:

A clean, keyboard-driven tracker workstation
with built-in DSP and controlled complexity.

Not a plugin host.
Not a feature monster.
Not a visual showcase.

A structured musical tool.
